dk Ostrava]]\n| caps12 = 44\n| goals12 = 15\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20131997\n| nationalteam1 = Czech Republic U15\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 1997\u20131998\n| nationalteam2 = Czech Republic U16\n| nationalcaps2 = 5\n| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| nationalyears3 = 1998\n| nationalteam3 = [[Czech Republic national under-17 football team|Czech Republic U17]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 4\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 1998\u20132000\n| nationalteam4 = Czech Republic U18\n| nationalcaps4 = 19\n| nationalgoals4 = 5\n| nationalyears5 = 1999\u20132002\n| nationalteam5 = [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic U21]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 19\n| nationalgoals5 = 9\n| nationalyears6 = 2001\u20132012\n| nationalteam6 = [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 93\n| nationalgoals6 = 41\n| club-update = 9 August 2019\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{medal|Country|{{fb|CZE}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|B|[[UEFA Euro 2004|2004 Portugal]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2002 Switzerland]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Milan Baro\u0161''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8m\u026alan \u02c8baro\u0283}}; born 28 October 1981) is a Czech [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for [[FC Ban\u00edk Ostrava|Ban\u00edk Ostrava]] in the [[Czech First League]].\n\nIn 2005, he was part of the [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] team which won the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]. He went on to win [[Ligue 1]] with [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] in 2007, the [[FA Cup]] with [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in 2008 and the [[S\u00fcper Lig]] with [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in 2012. He has also had spells with Ban\u00edk Ostrava, where he started his career, and English club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].\n\nBorn in [[Vala\u0161sk\u00e9 Mezi\u0159\u00ed\u010d\u00ed]], Baro\u0161 represented the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic international team]] in 93 matches, scoring on 41 occasions. He won the [[UEFA Euro 2004#Awards|Golden Boot]] as top scorer of the [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] tournament, where his nation reached the semi-finals. He went on to play in three more major international tournaments. His 41 goals for the Czech Republic is second behind only [[Jan Koller]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBaro\u0161 was born in the Czech town of [[Vala\u0161sk\u00e9 Mezi\u0159\u00ed\u010d\u00ed]].<ref name=lcfinal03/> He grew up in the village of [[Vigantice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moravskoslezsky.denik.cz/fotbal_region/srdcar-baniku-milan-baros-na-vigantice-nedam-dopustit-20130301.html|title=Srdca\u0159 Ban\u00edku Milan Baro\u0161: Na Vigantice ned\u00e1m dopustit|language=Czech|work=[[Den\u00edk]]|date=2 March 2013|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> In 2009, he married Tereza Frankov\u00e1,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Milan Baros gizlice evlendi|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/spor/futbol/12196565.asp|language=Turkish|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|date=2 August 2009|accessdate=2 August 2009}}</ref> who he started dating in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://revue.idnes.cz/milan-baros-predstavil-pritelkyni-dt2-/sex.aspx?c=A051208_113133_sex_lf|title=Milan Baro\u0161 p\u0159edstavil p\u0159\u00edtelkyni|language=Czech|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=8 December 2005|accessdate=19 February 2014}}</ref> Their son Patrik was born on 1 September 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://revue.idnes.cz/fotbalistovi-milanu-barosovi-se-v-noci-narodil-syn-f8t-/sex.aspx?c=A090902_110706_sex_ved|title=Fotbalistovi Milanu Baro\u0161ovi se v noci narodil syn|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=2 September 2009|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 November 2007, Baro\u0161 was arrested in France while driving at {{convert|271|km/h|abbr=on}} in his black [[Ferrari F430]], on a freeway limited to {{convert|130|km/h|abbr=on}}. Stopped by [[French police]] between [[Lyon]] and [[Geneva]] in the region of [[Ain]], the local authorities said the radar reading of 271&nbsp;km/h was the fastest speed ever recorded in the region, surpassing the previous mark of {{convert|248|km/h|abbr=on}} set by a motorcyclist in 2000. As a result, Baro\u0161 had his car and licence confiscated and had to return to Lyon in a taxi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/02112007/58/ligue-1-baros-caught-speeding-170mph.html |title=Ligue 1 \u2013 Baros caught speeding at {{convert|170|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} |publisher=Eurosport |date=2 November 2007 |accessdate=26 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104071653/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/02112007/58/ligue-1-baros-caught-speeding-170mph.html |archivedate= 4 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nAs a boy, Baro\u0161 played for youth clubs in Vigantice and [[Ro\u017enov pod Radho\u0161t\u011bm]] before joining the youth team of [[FC Ban\u00edk Ostrava|Ban\u00edk Ostrava]] at the age of 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/databanka.aspx?t=hrac&id=3000263|title=Milan Baro\u0161 Antalyaspor Kul\u00fcb\u00fc|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> In 1998, he made his debut for the club in the [[Czech First League]], the top division of Czech football, becoming a regular over the next few seasons.<ref name=jerabek>{{cite book |last=Je\u0159\u00e1bek|first=Lubo\u0161|title=\u010cesk\u00fd a \u010deskoslovensk\u00fd fotbal \u2013 lexikon osobnost\u00ed a klub\u016f|year=2007|publisher=Grada Publishing|location=Prague|language=Czech|isbn=978-80-247-1656-5|page=15}}</ref> In 2000, he won the Talent of the Year award at the [[Czech Footballer of the Year]] awards.<ref>{{in lang|cs}} [http://nv.fotbal.cz/fotbalista-roku/historie/index.php Historie ankety Fotbalista roku] at [[\u010cMFS]] website</ref> He was described by the Czech News Agency in the 2000\u201301 season as \"perhaps the biggest star of the [Czech] football league\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/utocnik-baros-zazil-ostry-faul-dml-/fotbal.aspx?c=A010404_231214_fotbal_rou|title=\u00dato\u010dn\u00edk Baro\u0161 za\u017eil ostr\u00fd faul|language=Czech|work=Czech News Agency|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=4 April 2001|accessdate=11 March 2014|quote=Mo\u017en\u00e1 nejv\u011bt\u0161\u00ed hv\u011bzda fotbalov\u00e9 ligy}}</ref> He played his last game for the club on 2 December 2001, in a 1\u20130 loss at [[FK Viktoria \u017di\u017ekov|Viktoria \u017di\u017ekov]].<ref name=backtobanik>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/milan-baros-v-baniku-ostrava-dg0-/fotbal.aspx?c=A130218_113244_fotbal_min|title=Baro\u0161 podepsal smlouvu na rok a p\u016fl, plat v\u011bnuje v Ban\u00edku na ml\u00e1de\u017e|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=18 February 2013|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> During his time in Ostrava, he scored 23 league goals in 76 appearances.<ref name=backtobanik/>\n\n===Liverpool===\nBaro\u0161 joined [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2002 in a transfer worth [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3.2 million,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/3872443.stm|title=Liverpool deny Baros bid|work=BBC Sport|date=8 July 2004|accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> although he did not move straight away due to delays in obtaining a work permit for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/liverpool-zada-o-pracovni-povoleni-pro-barose-f42-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A011114_135243_fot_zahranici_mn|title=Liverpool \u017e\u00e1d\u00e1 o pracovn\u00ed povolen\u00ed pro Baro\u0161e|language=Czech|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=14 November 2001|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> He made his club debut in a [[UEFA Champions League]] tie away to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on 13 March;<ref name=dm02>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-91575104.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610222241/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-91575104.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2014|title=EVERYTHING YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT MILAN BAROS|work=Daily Mail|location=London|date=16 September 2002|accessdate=11 January 2014}}{{subscription required|via=Highbeam Research}}</ref> he played last 16 minutes in place of [[Emile Heskey]] as the match finished goalless.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dominic |last=Fifield |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/mar/14/championsleague.sport4|title=Liverpool face do-or-die Roma date after night of stalemates|publisher=The Guardian|date=14 March 2002|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> It was his only appearance of the [[2001\u201302 Liverpool F.C. season|2001\u201302 season]].<ref name=dm02/>\n\nIn the [[2002\u201303 Liverpool F.C. season|2002\u201303 season]], Baro\u0161 scored twice on his [[Premier League|Premiership]] debut away to [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on 14 September 2002, as Liverpool won 3&ndash;2 away.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2254693.stm | title=Baros makes his mark |work=BBC News | date=16 February 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 was a substitute in the [[2003 Football League Cup Final]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. He entered the game in the second half, but did not play to the end of the game, being substituted himself a minute before the end of the game.<ref name=lcfinal03>{{cite news |first=Amy |last=Lawrence |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/feb/27/newsstory.carlingcup04051 |title=Baros finally has chance to settle old score|publisher=The Observer|date=27 February 2005|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> Liverpool won the game 2\u20130 to win the cup, the first major trophy of Baro\u0161' career.<ref name=lcfinal03/> Towards the end of the season, he scored twice in a 6\u20130 away win over already-relegated [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in April 2003.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Lacey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/apr/28/match.sport15 |title=Owen conducts Liverpool rites of spring|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 April 2003|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> He ended his first season in the Premiership with 12 goals for the club.\n\nBaro\u0161 broke his ankle in a September 2003 match against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], a match which also saw teammate [[Jamie Carragher]] sustain a broken leg.<ref>{{cite news| title=Baros suffers broken ankle|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 September 2003|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/3106824.stm|accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> Baro\u0161 subsequently missed five months of football and scored just two goals in the [[2003\u201304 Liverpool F.C. season|2003\u201304 season]].<ref name=bbchoullier>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/3845213.stm|title=Baros hits out at Houllier|work=BBC Sport|date=28 June 2004|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> His first goal came in a league match against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in February 2004,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/3507625.stm | title=Leeds 2-2 Liverpool |work=BBC Sport | date=29 February 2004 | accessdate= 14 January 2014}}</ref> while his other goal was in March in a 1\u20131 Champions League draw against [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/3497310.stm | title=Liverpool 1-1 Marseille |work=BBC Sport | date=11 March 2004 | accessdate= 14 January 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 would later claim that had manager [[G\u00e9rard Houllier]] stayed at the club after the summer of 2004, he would have put in a transfer request.<ref name=bbchoullier/> As it was, Houllier left the club and was replaced by [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/3776857.stm | title=Liverpool appoint Benitez |work=BBC Sport | date=16 June 2004 | accessdate= 11 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nBaro\u0161 entered the [[2004\u201305 Liverpool F.C. season|2004\u201305 season]] having been the top goalscorer in the summer's [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]]<ref name=\"top\"/> tournament. With [[Michael Owen]] and Emile Heskey having been sold and new signing [[Djibril Ciss\u00e9]] out with a long-term injury, Baro\u0161 was now Liverpool's only senior striker.<ref name=\"top\">{{cite web|first=Ian|last=Doyle|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-124647257|title=Baros Secures Reds Win, but Can He Silence His Doubters?|work=Daily Post|location=Liverpool|date=15 November 2004|accessdate=17 January 2014}}{{subscription required|via=Questia Online Library}}</ref> Despite being the club's joint top scorer with 13 goals, including a [[hat-trick]] against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]],<ref>{{cite news| title=Baros hat-trick delights Benitez|publisher=BBC Sport|date=13 November 2004|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/4006303.stm|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Spaniard [[Fernando Morientes]] was preferred to Baro\u0161 in Liverpool's starting lineup for the [[2005 Football League Cup Final|League Cup Final]], a match they lost to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Vasek|last=Kadlec|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11669/2328184/baros-blasts-quit-talk|title=Baros blasts quit talk|work=Sky Sports|date=|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref> However, he did start the [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final|2005 Champions League Final]], being substituted after 85 minutes as the game finished 3\u20133 in normal time.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4580077.stm|title=AC Milan/Liverpool player ratings|work=BBC Sport|date=25 May 2005|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref> Liverpool went on to win the match on penalties. Baro\u0161 reportedly dropped the trophy during the team's celebration, leaving a dent, but Liverpool decided not to mend it because it \"added to the character\" of the trophy.<ref>{{Cite news\n|title= Liverpool damage Champions trophy.\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_4600000/newsid_4603500/4603587.stm\n|publisher=CBBC\n|date=2 June 2005\n|accessdate=8 October 2009\n}}</ref> He finished the season with 13 goals, becoming the joint-top scorer for the club.<ref name=villa-transfer>{{Cite news|title=Baros completes transfer to Villa|publisher=BBC Sport|date=23 August 2005|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/4154498.stm|accessdate =16 February 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 also received his first red card during the campaign, being sent off for a high challenge on [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]'s [[Alan Stubbs]] in the [[Merseyside derby]] on 20 March.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liverpool 2-1 Everton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4343223.stm|accessdate=2 November 2014|work=BBC Sport|date=20 March 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2005, former manager G\u00e9rard Houllier, then with French club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]], made an approach to sign Baro\u0161. The player rejected the approach,<ref>{{Cite news| title =Lyon still hopeful of Baros deal |publisher=BBC Sport | date =21 June 2005 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/4103230.stm | accessdate =16 February 2014 }}</ref> but only made two substitute appearances for Liverpool in the [[2005\u201306 FA Premier League|2005\u201306 season]] before leaving the club. He left Liverpool with league figures of 19 goals in 68 appearances.<ref name=portugal08>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-91575104.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610222241/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-91575104.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2014|title=Baros again fails to score in return to Czech team as Portugal wins 3-1 at Euro 2008|work=AP Worldstream|date=11 June 2008|accessdate=11 January 2014}}{{subscription required|via=Highbeam Research}}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\nBaro\u0161 moved to Premiership side [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] for a fee of \u00a36.5 million in August 2005, signing a four-year contract.<ref name=villa-transfer/> He was given the number 10 shirt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+You've+got+to+hand+it+to+us%3B+VILLA+4+EVERTON+0+Villa+make...-a0140186979|title=Football: You've got to hand it to us; VILLA 4 EVERTON 0 Villa make the most of their chances to stage four-goal demolition.|first=Bill|last=Howell|work=Birmingham Mail|date=27 December 2005|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> Just ten minutes into his Aston Villa debut, he scored the only goal in his new team's league victory over Blackburn.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4168746.stm|title=Aston Villa 1-0 Blackburn|work=BBC Sport|date=27 August 2005|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>  He played a crucial role in Villa's [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] second round victory against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in September.<ref name=wycombe>{{cite web|first=Jon|last=Brodkin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/sep/21/match.astonvilla|title=From farce to class as Villa turn the tables on Chairboys|work=The Guardian|date=21 September 2005|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> With Villa trailing 3\u20131 at half time, Baro\u0161 scored shortly after the beginning of the second half and won a penalty, which [[Gareth Barry]] converted.<ref name=wycombe/> He also provided the cross for Barry's second goal of the game as Villa scored seven goals in the second half, resulting in a final score of 8\u20133, their biggest win in over 40 years.<ref name=wycombe/> He set up the first Aston Villa goal in a November match against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in dubious circumstances; back-heeling the ball, which \"looked to have gone out of play\" to [[Aaron Hughes]].<ref name=hughes-backheel>{{Cite news|title=Sunderland 1-3 Aston Villa|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 November 2005|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4430998.stm|accessdate =21 January 2014}}</ref> Hughes' pass found [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]], who opened the scoring against his old club. He later scored a goal himself in the same game, which ended 3\u20131 to Villa.<ref name=hughes-backheel/>\n\nIn the [[Boxing Day]] match against Everton, Baro\u0161 was involved thoroughly in the proceedings. He opened the scoring in the 35th minute, having handled the ball immediately beforehand.<ref name=hands3points>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2005-12-27/baros-hands-villa-three-points-against-everton/769530|title=Baros hands Villa three points against Everton|work=AFP|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=27 December 2005|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> This was not punished and the referee awarded a goal.<ref name=hands3points/> Baro\u0161 subsequently celebrated in front of the travelling Everton fans, making a gesture as if to listen to them.<ref name=handofbaros>{{cite web|first=Stuart|last=James|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/dec/27/match.sport14|title=Hand of Baros throws Everton into despair|work=The Guardian|date=27 December 2005|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> A number of missiles from the crowd were subsequently thrown in Baro\u0161' direction.<ref name=handofbaros/> The goal was just his third in what Glenn Moore of ''[[The Independent]]'' described as \"an indifferent season\" for Baro\u0161.<ref name=indifferent>{{cite web|first=Glenn|last=Moore|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/aston-villa-4-everton-0-baros-on-hand-to-lift-villa-and-trigger-another-everton-collapse-520741.html|title=Aston Villa 4 Everton 0: Baros on hand to lift Villa and trigger another Everton collapse|work=The Independent|date=27 December 2005|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> He went on to score his second goal of the game, and Villa's fourth, earning him [[man of the match]] honours.<ref name=indifferent/> Baro\u0161 scored twice in January 2006's fourth round [[FA Cup]] win against [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/4634282.stm|title=Aston Villa 3-1 Port Vale|work=BBC Sport|date=28 January 2006|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> and added another in the following round's 1\u20131 draw with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/4703890.stm|title=Aston Villa 1-1 Man City|work=BBC Sport|date=19 February 2006|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> Late in the season, he scored two goals in the [[Second City derby]] against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] at Villa Park, marking his 11th and 12th goals of the season and winning another man of the match award.<ref>{{cite web|first=Neil|last=Moxley|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-144581153|title=Baros Drops Blues Deeper in the Mire; Aston Vila 3 BIRMINGHAM 1|work=Daily Mail|location=London|date=17 April 2006|accessdate=20 January 2014}}{{subscription required|via=Questia Online Library}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Ged|last=Scott|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-144591323|title=Villa Focus on Moving Forward from Derby Double|work=The Birmingham Post|date=18 April 2006|accessdate=20 January 2014}}{{subscription required|via=Questia Online Library}}</ref> He would score no further goals that season.\n\nBaro\u0161 failed to score at the start of the [[2006\u201307 Aston Villa F.C. season|2006\u201307 season]], leading new manager [[Martin O'Neill]] to challenge him in October to prove himself before the January [[transfer window]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/sport/football/clubs/astonvilla/article2297204.ece|title=Baros challenged to prove his worth as O\u2019Neill gets tough|work=The Times|first=Peter|last=Lansley|date=28 October 2006|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> He subsequently scored his first goal of the season in December 2006, eight months since scoring his last one, with a close-range equaliser against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in a 2\u20132 draw.<ref name=sheff-u-goal>{{Cite news| title =Sheff Utd 2-2 Aston Villa |publisher=BBC Sport | date =11 December 2006 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/6201524.stm | accessdate =16 February 2014 }}</ref> Although he also managed to score for Aston Villa in a 2\u20131 loss to Manchester United in the FA Cup,<ref>{{Cite news| title =Man Utd 2-1 Aston Villa |publisher=BBC Sport | date =7 January 2007 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/6213959.stm | accessdate =16 February 2014 }}</ref> he left the club in January 2007, having scored just once in 17 league matches that season.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Ian|last1=Willoughby|first2=Caroline|last2=Bauer|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/czech-football-star-milan-baros-looking-to-revive-career-at-lyon|title=Czech football star Milan Baros looking to revive career at Lyon|work=[[Radio Prague]]|date=23 January 2007|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Lyon===\nOn 22 January 2007, Baro\u0161 signed with French side Lyon, signing a three-and-a-half year contract and reuniting with former manager G\u00e9rard Houllier from his time at Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/potvrzeno-baros-prestoupil-do-lyonu-dsv-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A070122_135705_fot_zahranici_min|title=Potvrzeno, Baro\u0161 p\u0159estoupil do Lyonu|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=22 January 2007|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> The deal swapped Baro\u0161 with Lyon striker [[John Carew]], who joined Aston Villa on a three-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite news| title=Villa secure Carew in Baros swap|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 January 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/6280575.stm|accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> Just two days after joining the club, he made his Lyon debut in a league match against [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]]. He appeared as a substitute, as league leaders Lyon lost 2\u20131 for their first home defeat of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2007/01/26/2003346463|title=Vintage Bordeaux performance leaves Lyon feeling blue|work=AP|publisher=Taipei Times|date=26 January 2007|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 took part in that year's [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], featuring as a substitute in a 0\u20130 draw in [[Rome]] against [[A.S. Roma|Roma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/archives/2007/0222/sport/cards-galore-as-roma-and-lyon-fail-to-score-26164.html|title=Cards galore as Roma and Lyon fail to score|work=Irish Examiner|first=Jan|last=Kolver|date=22 February 2007|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> He played no further part in that season's Champions League campaign, as he remained on the bench in the return leg as Lyon were eliminated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2007-03-07/roma-inflict-champions-league-misery-on-lyon/2210448|title=Roma inflict Champions League misery on Lyon|work=AFP|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=7 March 2007|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Baro\u0161 was accused of making a racist gesture towards his [[Cameroon]]ian opponent [[St\u00e9phane Mbia]] during Lyon's match against [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]] on 18 April.<ref name=Frenchsuspension>{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/05/03/sports/EU-SPT-SOC-Lyon-Baros-Suspended.php |title=French league suspends Baros for three matches, clears him of racist gesture|publisher=International Herald Tribune|date=3 May 2007|accessdate=12 January 2014|archivedate=5 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205081500/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/05/03/sports/EU-SPT-SOC-Lyon-Baros-Suspended.php}}</ref> After having been fouled by Mbia several times, Baro\u0161 held his nose in front of Mbia and waved his hand as if to waft away an unpleasant smell.<ref name=Frenchsuspension/> In the ensuing controversy, Baro\u0161 insisted that his gesture was not intended to be racist in any way, and he was only trying to tell Mbia to get out of his face and leave him alone.<ref name=Frenchsuspension/> Baro\u0161 and Mbia were brought before an official disciplinary hearing of the [[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] (LFP), which ruled that Baro\u0161 was innocent of racist behaviour, but he was nevertheless suspended for the remaining three games of the season for unsportsmanlike conduct.<ref name=Frenchsuspension/> The end of the season saw Lyon win the league title, but nonetheless manager Houllier left the club.<ref>{{cite news| title=Houllier steps down as Lyon coach|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 May 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6692479.stm|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nBaro\u0161 scored in Lyon's opening game of the [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308 season]] as his club won 2\u20130 against [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SPORT/football/08/05/france.lyon/index.html|title=Lyon open new campaign with a win|work=CNN|date=5 August 2007|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref> However, he played significantly less under new manager [[Alain Perrin]], making just six starts and scoring a total of three league goals.<ref name=pompeyloan>{{cite news| title=Milan Baros agrees Portsmouth loan deal|publisher=Telegraph|date=27 January 2008|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2290162/Milan-Baros-agrees-Portsmouth-loan-deal.html#|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> In mid-November, Baro\u0161 revealed a break down in his relationship with Perrin and hinted at a move to another club.<ref>{{cite news| title=Baros set for Lyon exit|publisher=Sky Sports|date=15 November 2007|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11800/2882567/|accessdate=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth===\nBaro\u0161 joined Premier League side [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on loan from Lyon in January 2008 until the end of the season, with the option of making the move permanent at the end of the loan.<ref name=pompeyloan/> Baro\u0161 played a significant role in the club [[2007\u201308 FA Cup|winning the 2008 FA Cup]]. He won Portsmouth's match-winning penalty kick in the quarter-final at Manchester United and assisted [[Nwankwo Kanu]]'s deciding goal in the semi final match against West Bromwich Albion with a suspected handball that went unnoticed by both the referee and his assistant.<ref>{{cite news| title=Man Utd 0-1 Portsmouth|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 March 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/7272806.stm|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Baros 'handball' angers Phillips|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 April 2008|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/7332240.stm|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> The final match of Baro\u0161' loan spell was the [[2008 FA Cup Final]] victory over [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], where he appeared as an 87th-minute substitute for Kanu.<ref name=dm22may08>{{cite news| title=Pompey set to release Davis, Baros and Lauren|publisher=Daily Mail|date=22 May 2008|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1021236/Pompey-set-release-Davis-Baros-Lauren.html|accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref> By the end of the season, Baro\u0161 had played 16 matches for Portsmouth, including seven as a substitute, although he failed to score.<ref name=dm22may08/> He was one of a number of Portsmouth players to be absent at the team parade after the club won the FA Cup, leading to speculation he could have played his last game for the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/transfer-news-and-speculation-23-may-832743.html|title=Davis likely to leave Pompey|work=The Independent|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> At the end of the season, Baro\u0161 returned to Lyon.<ref name=signedgalatasaray>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/transfer-news-and-speculation-27-august-909537.html|title=Baros quits France for move to Turkey|work=The Independent|date=27 August 2008|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Galatasaray===\n[[File:Barossamsun.jpg|thumb|Baro\u0161 playing for Galatasaray in 2011]]\nIn August 2008, Baro\u0161 joined Turkish champions [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] from Lyon for a fee of \u20ac4.7 million.<ref name=signedgalatasaray/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actusnews.com/documents/ACTUS-0-3288-OL-DDR-0809-GB.pdf|title=Olympique Lyonnais Group Financial Report 2008\u201309|publisher=Actusnewswire.com|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> He made his first appearance against [[Kayserispor]], playing the last 15 minutes. Baro\u0161 scored his first two goals for the club in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] first round, first leg game against [[AC Bellinzona|Bellinzona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galatasaray.org/en/futbol/uefa/haber/124.php|title=Match Report \u2013 Bellinzona:3 Galatasaray:4|publisher=Galatasaray.org|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> Three days later, in his first league start, he once again scored two goals against [[Kocaelispor]], with Galatasaray going on to win the match 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galatasaray.org/en/futbol/superlig/haber/132.php|title=Match Report \u2013 Kocaeli:1 Galatasaray:4|publisher=Galatasaray.org|date=21 September 2008|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> On 21 December 2008, Baro\u0161 scored a hat-trick in the 4\u20132 [[S\u00fcper Lig]] [[Be\u015fikta\u015f\u2013Galatasaray rivalry|derby]] win against [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]], converting two penalties and scoring one from open play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galatasaray.org/en/futbol/superlig/haber/307.php|title=Match Report \u2013 Galatasaray:4 Be\u015fikta\u015f:2|publisher=Galatasaray.org|date=21 December 2008|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> He scored another hat-trick later in the season against [[Hacettepe S.K.|Hacettepe]].<ref name=4hattricks>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-222803-simpson-and-baros-steal-the-show-with-hat-tricks.html|title=Simpson and Baros steal the show with hat tricks|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=28 September 2010|accessdate=15 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222203642/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-222803-simpson-and-baros-steal-the-show-with-hat-tricks.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He finished the [[2008\u201309 S\u00fcper Lig|2008\u201309 season]] as the S\u00fcper Lig top scorer with 20 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tablest/turktops.html|title=Turkey - Topscorers|work=RSSSF.com|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nBaro\u0161 scored his first goal of the [[2009\u201310 S\u00fcper Lig|2009\u201310 season]] in his third league game when he scored twice in a 4\u20131 win against Kayserispor.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=275301&cc=5739 |title=Match: Galatasaray v Kayserispor - Turkish Super Lig - ESPN FC |publisher=Soccernet-assets.espn.go.com |date=23 August 2009 |accessdate=19 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324055121/http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=275301&cc=5739 |archive-date=24 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His next two goals came on 13 September where Galatasaray played rivals Be\u015fikta\u015f. Galatasaray won the match 3\u20130, with Baro\u0161 scoring his third and fourth goals of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=275991&cc=5739|title=Match: Galatasaray v Besiktas - Turkish Super Lig - ESPN FC|publisher=Soccernet-assets.espn.go.com|date=12 September 2009|accessdate=19 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324055129/http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=275991&cc=5739|archive-date=24 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He scored a total of five times in ten matches before breaking his left foot in two places after a tackle by [[Emre Bel\u00f6zo\u011flu]] in the [[K\u0131talar Aras\u0131 Derbi|Fenerbah\u00e7e\u2013Galatasaray derby]] on 25 October 2009.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=943236.html|title=Baro\u0161 return delayed by surgery|work=UEFA|date=14 January 2010|accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref> He returned to action four and a half months later on 14 March 2010 for a game against [[MKE Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc|Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc]], scoring a goal on his comeback.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galatasaray.org/en/kulup/haber/809.php|title=Medical Report for Milan Baro\u0161|publisher=Galatasaray.org|date=26 October 2009|accessdate=12 December 2009}}</ref> During the season, he scored his third hat-trick for the club in a match against [[Diyarbakirspor]].<ref name=4hattricks/> He finished the season with league figures of 11 goals in 17 matches.<ref name=galatasary-extension>{{citation|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1511436.html|title=Galatasaray secure Baro\u0161 for two more years|work=UEFA|date=8 August 2010|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, a week before the start of the [[2010\u201311 S\u00fcper Lig]], he extended his contract with Galatasaray for two seasons, keeping him contracted to the club until the end of the 2012\u201313 season.<ref name=galatasary-extension/> Although he had been injured during pre-season training,<ref name=galatasary-extension/> Baro\u0161 appeared as a substitute in his club's [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League qualification]] match against [[FC Karpaty Lviv|Karpaty Lviv]], scoring twice as Galatasaray returned from 2\u20130 down to draw the match.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1515366.html|title=Baro\u0161 denies Karpaty a bigger upset|work=UEFA|date=20 August 2010|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref> At the end of September, he scored his fourth hat-trick for the club against [[\u0130stanbul B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyespor (football)|Istanbul B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyespor]], although he failed to complete the game due to an injury.<ref name=4hattricks/> He scored two more goals in a 4\u20132 loss against Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc on 17 October, but was injured again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-224708-lions-fall-flat-coach-rijkaard-going-going-.html|title=Lions fall flat; coach Rijkaard going, going...|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=19 October 2010|accessdate=15 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222203546/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-224708-lions-fall-flat-coach-rijkaard-going-going-.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Baro\u0161 was suspended for three matches in March 2011 after insulting referee [[F\u0131rat Ayd\u0131nus]] in a match against Be\u015fikta\u015f.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-239197-lions-to-host-trabzonspor-behind-closed-doors.html|title=Lions to host Trabzonspor behind closed doors|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=26 March 2011|accessdate=15 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222203645/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-239197-lions-to-host-trabzonspor-behind-closed-doors.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By the end of the season, Baro\u0161 had appeared in 17 league games and scored 9 goals.<ref name=Soccerway-profile>{{Soccerway|milan-baros/267}}. Retrieved 19 November 2013.</ref>\n\nGalatasaray started the [[2011\u201312 S\u00fcper Lig|2011\u201312 season]] well and were top of the league in January, having won eight consecutive league matches.<ref name=8wins>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/galatasaray-makes-it-8-for-8-in-super-league.aspx?pageID=238&nID=11032&NewsCatID=362|title=Galatasaray makes it 8 for 8 in Super League|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]]|date=9 January 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 did not start a match for his club for four weeks,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-264049-lions-can-also-have-9-lives-galatasaray-lions-subdue-sivas-with-9-men-at-arena.html|title=Lions can also have 9 lives: Galatasaray Lions subdue Sivas with 9 men at Arena|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=27 November 2011|accessdate=16 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204259/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-264049-lions-can-also-have-9-lives-galatasaray-lions-subdue-sivas-with-9-men-at-arena.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but scored an important goal against [[Samsunspor]] in the eighth match of the streak.<ref name=8wins/> The club won a ninth-straight game, with Baro\u0161 scoring his seventh goal of the season, in the 5\u20131 win against [[Kardemir D. \u00c7. Karab\u00fckspor|Kardemir Karab\u00fckspor]], although he left the game with an injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-269184-leader-galatasaray-aims-for-10-straight-victories-at-eskisehir.html|title=Leader Galatasaray aims for 10 straight victories at Eski\u015fehir|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=22 January 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204253/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-269184-leader-galatasaray-aims-for-10-straight-victories-at-eskisehir.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He returned from injury in a February match against [[Antalyaspor]], coming on as a substitute, but was on the field of play just 15 minutes before receiving a [[penalty card#red card|red card]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-270309-galatasaray-falters-again-black-sea-storm-surges-on.html|title=Galatasaray falters again, Black Sea Storm surges on|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=2 February 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204256/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-270309-galatasaray-falters-again-black-sea-storm-surges-on.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His dismissal resulted in a three-match suspension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-271051-leader-galatasaray-hosts-kayserispor-in-crucial-league-match.html|title=Leader Galatasaray hosts Kayserispor in crucial league match|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=10 February 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204305/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-271051-leader-galatasaray-hosts-kayserispor-in-crucial-league-match.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Baro\u0161 scored his last goal for the club in April 2012 in the last match of the regular season against [[Manisaspor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-276892-regular-season-over-playoffs-set-to-begin.html|title=Regular season over, playoffs set to begin|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=9 April 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204357/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-276892-regular-season-over-playoffs-set-to-begin.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Baro\u0161 was told by then-coach [[Fatih Terim]] that he would not play for the club any more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-296616-agent-coming-to-decide-baross-fate.html|title=Agent coming to decide Baros's fate|publisher=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=16 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204249/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-296616-agent-coming-to-decide-baross-fate.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He played no competitive football after Euro 2012 and finally left the club in February 2013.<ref name=backtobanik/>\n\n===Return to Ban\u00edk Ostrava===\nOn 18 February 2013, Czech club Ban\u00edk Ostrava announced that Baro\u0161 had rejoined the club where he started his career, signing a one-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Milan Baros leaves Galatasaray for Czech Republic's Banik Ostrava|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/20130218/milan-baros-czech-republic-galatasaray.ap/|work=Associated Press|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref> Under the terms of the contract, his salary was donated to support the youth club of the team.<ref name=backtobanik/> Having not played a competitive match since 21 June of the previous year,<ref name=backtobanik/> he played his first match of the season on 23 February, coming on as a substitute in the 0\u20130 home draw with [[SK Dynamo \u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice|Dynamo \u010cesk\u00e9 Bud\u011bjovice]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Milan Baro\u0161 match log|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/02/23/czech-republic/czech-liga/fc-banik-ostrava/sk-dynamo-ceske-budejovice/1315509/|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref> He scored a hat-trick in Ostrava's 3\u20130 league victory against [[FC Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9|Hradec Kr\u00e1lov\u00e9]] on 9 March 2013, his first hat-trick in the top flight of Czech football.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/baros-prvni-hattrick-v-ceske-lize-dqt-/fotbal.aspx?c=A130309_213358_fotbal_min|title=Baro\u0161: Statistiky nejsou d\u016fle\u017eit\u00e9, ale zase u\u017e m\u016f\u017eu hr\u00e1t v klidu|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=9 March 2013|accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Antalyaspor===\nOn 16 July 2013, Baro\u0161 agreed a one-year contract with Turkish club Antalyaspor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2013-07-16/football/striker-baros-moves-to-turkeys-antalyaspor-2090565632/ |title=Striker Baros moves to Turkey's Antalyaspor - The Malta Independent |publisher=Independent.com.mt |date= |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> He made his club debut in August, appearing as a substitute in a 0\u20130 S\u00fcper Lig draw against [[Kayseri Erciyesspor]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/vysledky-evropskych-fotbalovych-lig-dwd-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A130817_212704_fot_zahranici_vl|title=Jun s Fo\u0159tem dali g\u00f3l, Baro\u0161 a Necid hr\u00e1li poprv\u00e9 ligu za nov\u00e9 t\u00fdmy|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=17 August 2013|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Antalyaspor against [[Bursaspor]] in August, then his second against [[\u00c7aykur Rizespor|Rizespor]] in October.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/zahranicni-fotbalove-souteze-pavel-fort-ffa-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A131005_201025_fot_zahranici_pes|title=\u00dato\u010dn\u00edk Fo\u0159t d\u00e1v\u00e1 g\u00f3l za g\u00f3lem, Baro\u0161 za\u0159\u00eddil v\u00fdhru Antalyasporu|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=5 October 2013|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> He suffered damage to his [[anterior cruciate ligament]] (ACL) in December 2013, ruling him out of action for the rest of the season. Baro\u0161 returned to the Czech Republic for treatment in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/baros-operace-kolena-0lt-/fot_zahranici.aspx?c=A140110_143203_fot_zahranici_min|title=Fotbalista Baro\u0161 p\u0159ilet\u00ed do Prahy, aby se podrobil operaci kolena|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=10 January 2014|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the Czech league===\n24 September 2014 saw Baro\u0161 re-join Ostrava; he signed a contract until the end of the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baro\u0161 podepsal smlouvu do konce ro\u010dn\u00edku, na prvn\u00ed z\u00e1pas si v\u0161ak po\u010dk\u00e1|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/milan-baros-se-stal-hracem-baniku-ostravu-smlouvu-ma-do-konce-sezony-1gb-/fotbal.aspx?c=A140924_121740_fotbal_min|language=Czech|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=24 September 2014|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> Following the end of the 2014\u201315 season, Baro\u0161 left Ostrava and signed a two-year contract with [[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/fotbalista-milan-baros-bude-hrat-za-klub-mlada-boleslav-p1h-/fotbal.aspx?c=A150619_114304_fotbal_pes|title=Dohodnuto, podeps\u00e1no. Baro\u0161 bude st\u0159\u00edlet g\u00f3ly za Mladou Boleslav|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=19 June 2015|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> Following the end of the 2015\u201316 season, Baro\u0161 left Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav and signed a two-year contract with Slovan Liberec.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://isport.blesk.cz/clanek/fotbal-synot-liga-rocnik-2016-17/274703/hotovo-baros-prosel-zdravotni-prohlidkou-a-uz-patri-liberci.html|title=HOTOVO! Baro\u0161 pro\u0161el zdravotn\u00ed prohl\u00eddkou a u\u017e pat\u0159\u00ed Liberci|language=Czech|work=isport.cz|publisher=\u010cTK|date=13 July 2016|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref> He only spent one of the two years at Liberec before returning to Ban\u00edk Ostrava in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Baro\u0161 se rozhodl pro Ban\u00edk! Bude n\u00e1m v Liberci chyb\u011bt, \u0159ekl Nezmar |url=https://isport.blesk.cz/clanek/fotbal-1-liga-rocnik-2017-18/306166/baros-se-rozhodl-pro-banik-bude-nam-v-liberci-chybet-rekl-nezmar.html |website=iSport |accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Milan Baro\u0161 2009.jpg|thumbnail|Baro\u0161 posing for a team photo before an international match in 2009|alt=refer to caption]]\n{{See also|List of international goals scored by Milan Baro\u0161}}\nBaro\u0161 started representing the Czech Republic in 1997, at under-15 level.<ref name=jerabek/> Over the next three years he moved up to play at higher age groups, specifically under-16, 17 and 18.<ref name=jerabek/> Baro\u0161 played in the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2000 Olympic tournament]], making three appearances for the team.<ref name=jerabek/> He took part in two other major tournaments at junior level: the [[2000 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]], at which the Czech Republic placed second, and the [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]], which the Czech Republic won.<ref name=jerabek/>\n\nBaro\u0161 made his first appearance for the senior national side on 25 April 2001 in a [[friendly match]] against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]],<ref name=bbceuro2004profile>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/czech_rep/players_to_watch/default.stm|title=Milan Baros|work=BBC Sport|date=26 May 2004|accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref> scoring on his debut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story?id=304166&cc=5739|title=Baros: First goal was vital|work=ESPN|date=27 June 2004|accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 and national teammate [[Pavel Nedv\u011bd]] were both shown the red card in a November 2001 qualification match for the following year's [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], as the Czech Republic were eliminated by Belgium.<ref>{{cite web|first=Frantisek|last=Bouc|url=http://www.praguepost.cz/archivescontent/34264-hey-hey-goodbye.html|title=HEY, HEY, GOODBYE|work=The Prague Post|date=21 November 2001|accessdate=16 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140117054227/http://www.praguepost.cz/archivescontent/34264-hey-hey-goodbye.html|archivedate=17 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt UEFA Euro 2004, Baro\u0161 scored the first goal for the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] in their first game of the tournament, a come-from-behind 2\u20131 victory over [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]].<ref name=cnnlatvia>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/SPORT/football/06/15/euro.czech/index.html|title=Baros strike sparks Czech comeback|work=CNN|date=16 June 2004|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> With the goal he became the youngest goalscorer at the European Championships for the Czech Republic.<ref name=cnnlatvia/> His second goal of the tournament came against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]; the Dutch team had taken a two-goal lead over the Czechs before [[Jan Koller]] scored from a Baro\u0161 pass.<ref name=bbchol>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3787537.stm|title=Holland 2-3 Czech Rep|work=BBC|date=19 June 2004|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 then scored before [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160micer]] completed the scoring, as the Czechs won the game 3\u20132.<ref name=bbchol/> The third group match saw the Czech Republic make nine changes to their starting lineup, having already qualified for the quarter-finals.<ref name=cnngermany>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/SPORT/football/06/23/euro.czech/index.html|title=Late Baros strike puts Germany out|work=CNN|date=23 June 2004|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> Baro\u0161 appeared as a substitute and scored the winning goal, as opponents [[Germany national football team|Germany]] failed to advance to the next stage of the tournament.<ref name=cnngermany/> Baro\u0161 added two goals in two minutes of the second half of the Czechs' quarter-final win over [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/28/sports/soccer-european-championships-baros-puts-czechs-in-semifinals.html|title=SOCCER: EUROPEAN CHAMPIONSHIPS; Baros Puts Czechs in Semifinals|work=The New York Times|date=28 June 2004|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref> and finished as the tournament's [[UEFA Euro 2004#Awards|Golden Boot]] winner with five goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2384217/Baros-eyes-move-to-Barcelona.html|title=Baros eyes move to Barcelona|work=The Telegraph|first=William|last=Johnson|date=6 August 2004|accessdate=11 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification for the 2006 World Cup]], Baro\u0161 scored five goals for his country, including four in consecutive matches in 2005.<ref name=rsssf-intgoals>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/baros-intlg.html |title=Milan Baros - Goals in International Matches |publisher=Rsssf.com |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> An injury to his foot, picked up in a match on 3 June, kept him out of [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] games against the [[United States national men's soccer team|United States]] and [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Pavla|last=Hor\u00e1kov\u00e1|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/news-2006-06-20|title=Baros may play for Czechs against Italy|work=[[Radio Prague]]|date=20 June 2006|accessdate=11 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111104815/http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/news-2006-06-20|archivedate=11 January 2014}}</ref> He did appear in the Czechs' final group game against [[Italy national football team|Italy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/italy-vs-czech-republic-italy-sends-czechs-packing-with-2-0-win-a-423081.html|title=Italy vs Czech Republic: Italy Sends Czechs Packing With 2-0 Win|work=Der Spiegel|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> but appeared unfit and left the game after 64 minutes to be replaced by [[David Jarol\u00edm]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=La Canfora|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/06/22/AR2006062200756.html|title=Limping Czechs Are Run Out|work=The Washington Post|date=23 June 2006|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Dampf|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/worldcup/2006-06-22-italy-czech_x.htm|title=Italy eliminates Czech Republic with 2-0 win|work=USA Today|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the run up to [[UEFA Euro 2008]], Baro\u0161 had not scored an international goal since March 2007.<ref name=portugal08/> He started the Czech Republic's second group game against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], but Portugal won 3\u20131 and Baro\u0161 failed to score.<ref name=portugal08/> Jan Koller was preferred to Baro\u0161 in the starting lineup for the next match, against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]].<ref name=turkey08>{{cite news| title=Turkey v Czech Republic - as it happened|publisher=Guardian|date=15 June 2008|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/15/euro2008groupa.turkey|accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> Despite neither playing in the match nor even being on the pitch, Baro\u0161 suffered the indignity of receiving a [[Yellow card (sport)|yellow card]] during stoppage time at the end of the match.<ref name=turkey08/>\n\nBaro\u0161 was banned indefinitely from playing for his national side in April 2009 after a breach of discipline, having attended a [[bar (establishment)|bar]] late at night.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-sport/article-23673835-details/Czechs+ban+Hammer+after+late+night+out/article.do |title=Czechs ban Hammer after late night out |work=This is London |date=8 April 2009 |accessdate=8 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410084557/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard-sport/article-23673835-details/Czechs%2Bban%2BHammer%2Bafter%2Blate%2Bnight%2Bout/article.do |archivedate=10 April 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, he was recalled to the national side after the appointment of [[Ivan Ha\u0161ek]] as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/fotbalovy-kouc-hasek-povolal-na-belgii-i-hrisniky-barose-a-sverkose-1pp-/fot_reprez.aspx?c=A090806_123254_fot_reprez_ot|title=Fotbalov\u00fd kou\u010d Ha\u0161ek povolal na Belgii i h\u0159\u00ed\u0161n\u00edky Baro\u0161e a Sv\u011brko\u0161e|language=Czech|work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=6 August 2009|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> On 12 August 2009, he marked his return to international duty with a goal from the penalty spot in the 3\u20131 home win against Belgium in a friendly match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2009-08-12-2451578677_x.htm|title=Czech Republic beats Belgium 3-1 in friendly|work=USA Today|date=12 August 2009|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> The following month, Baro\u0161 scored a career high of four goals against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]], in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification - UEFA Group 3|World Cup qualifier]] which the Czech Republic won 7\u20130.<ref name=4intgoals>{{cite web|url=http://www.praguepost.cz/sports/2262-hockey-season-starts-ha\u0161ek-returns.html|title=Hockey season starts, Ha\u0161ek returns|work=The Prague Post|date=16 September 2009|accessdate=24 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130063132/http://www.praguepost.cz/sports/2262-hockey-season-starts-ha%C5%A1ek-returns.html|archivedate=30 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In doing so, he became only the second player from the Czech Republic to score four goals in an international match.<ref name=4intgoals/> He was selected as part of the squad for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]]. After the tournament, during which he failed to score, Baro\u0161 announced his retirement from international football, having scored a total of 41 international goals in 93 matches.<ref name=int-retirement>{{cite news |first=Petr|last=\u0160ediv\u00fd|url=http://fotbal.idnes.cz/fotbalovy-utocnik-milan-baros-ukoncil-reprezentacni-karieru-ptv-/euro-2012.aspx?c=A120622_005001_euro-2012_pes|title=Baro\u0161 se rozlou\u010dil se spoluhr\u00e1\u010di a ukon\u010dil reprezenta\u010dn\u00ed kari\u00e9ru|language=Czech|work=idnes.cz|publisher=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES|date=22 June 2012|accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> His total of 41 international goals for his country is second only to strike partner Jan Koller, who holds the record with 55.<ref name=backtobanik/>\n\n==Style of play==\nBaro\u0161 gained the nickname \"the Ostravan Maradona\" in his native Czech Republic due to perceived similarities with the [[Diego Maradona|Argentine footballer of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Kenety|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/aston-villa-to-sign-on-czech-striker-milan-baros|title=Aston Villa to sign on Czech striker Milan Baros|work=[[Radio Prague]]|date=23 August 2005|accessdate=19 February 2014}}</ref> He was noted particularly for being a quick player with good [[dribbling]] skill.<ref name=bbceuro2004profile/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|1 February 2019}}. Source: League matches;<ref name=nft>{{NFT|1826|accessdate=}}</ref> Cup and League Cup matches<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espnfc.com/player/_/id/10396/milan-baros?cc=5739|title=Milan Baros Bio, Stats, News|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> Liverpool European matches<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/263|title=Player profile Milan Baros|publisher=www.lfchistory.net|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref> European club matches from 2006<ref name=Soccerway-profile/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[FC Ban\u00edk Ostrava|Ban\u00edk Ostrava]]\n|[[1998\u201399 Czech First League|1998\u201399]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Czech First League]]\n|6||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 Czech First League|1999\u20132000]]\n|29||6||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|