{"title_page": "USS Columbia (1836)", "text_new": "{{other ships|USS Columbia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{No footnotes|date=October 2011}}\n{|{{Infobox Ship Begin}}\n{{Infobox Ship Image\n|Ship image=Bombardment of Muckie.jpg\n|Ship image size=200px\n|Ship caption=''Columbia'' and ''John Adams'' bombarding Muckie, Sumatra, 1 January 1839\n}}\n{{Infobox Ship Career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1861}}\n|Ship maiden voyage=May 1838\n|Ship name=USS ''Columbia''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Washington Navy Yard]]\n|Ship laid down=1825\n|Ship launched=9 March 1836\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Burned, 21 April 1861\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox Ship Characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{Sclass-|Raritan|frigate}}\n|Ship tonnage= 1726\n|Ship length={{convert|175|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|45|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth={{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=Sail\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=480 officers and men\n|Ship armament=4 \u00d7 {{convert|8|in|mm|abbr=on}} smoothbore guns, 28 \u00d7 32-pounder (15 kg) guns, 22 \u00d7 42-pounder (19 kg) [[carronade]]s\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe first '''USS ''Columbia''''' of the [[United States Navy]] was a three-masted, wooden-hulled sailing [[frigate]] of the [[US Navy]], rated for 50 guns.  She was built at [[Washington Navy Yard]]. Her [[keel]] was laid in 1825, but as was typical of much Navy construction during this period, she was not launched until much later, on 9 March 1836.\n\nOn her first cruise, from May 1838 \u2013 June 1840 with Lieutenant [[George A. Magruder]] in command, ''Columbia'' rounded the [[Cape of Good Hope]] to become [[flagship]] of [[Commodore (United States)|Commodore]] [[George C. Read]] in the [[East India Squadron]]. She returned to the United States by way of [[Cape Horn]], becoming one of the first U.S. naval ships to circumnavigate the globe. She participated in the 1838 [[Second Sumatran Expedition]] in response to a Maylay attack on an American merchant vessel.\n\n''Columbia'' served as flagship of the [[Home Squadron]] from January\u2013May 1842; cruised on [[Brazil Squadron]] from July 1842 \u2013 February 1844 and in the [[Mediterranean Squadron (United States)|Mediterranean Squadron]] from May\u2013December 1844. She returned to the Brazil Squadron as flagship from November 1845 \u2013 October 1847, and was placed [[in ordinary]] at [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] upon her return home. Except for a cruise as flagship of the Home Squadron from January 1853 \u2013 March 1855, she remained at Norfolk until the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]]. ''Columbia'' was scuttled and burned by Union forces to avoid her capture by [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]] upon the surrender of Norfolk Navy Yard on 21 April 1861. Following the close of the war she was raised and sold at Norfolk on 10 October 1867.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Glossary of nautical terms]]\n*[[List of sailing frigates of the United States Navy]]\n\n==References==\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c11/columbia-i.htm}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite book|title=The Flag-ship: Or, A Voyage Around the World in the United States Frigate Columbia..|volume=Volume 2 of The Flag Ship, Or: A Voyage Around the World, in the United States Frigate Columbia; Attended by Her Consort the Sloop of War John Adams, and Bearing the Broad Pennant of Commodore George C. Read, Fitch Waterman Taylor|first=Fitch Waterman|last=Taylor|authorlink=Fitch Waterman Taylor|others=|edition=|year=1840|publisher=D. Appleton and Company|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ENoBAAAAYAAJ| ref=harv }}\n*[https://www.usna.edu/Library/sca/man-findingaids/MS_272.EAD.xml Journal of the U.S.S. ''Columbia'' and U.S.S. ''Mississippi'', 1843-1846 MS 272] held by Special Collection & Archives, Nimitz Library at the United States Naval Academy\n*[https://www.usna.edu/Library/sca/man-findingaids/MS_077.EAD.xml Watch, Quarter, and Station Bill of the U.S.S. ''Columbia'', 1844-1907 (bulk 1844) MS 77] held by Special Collection & Archives, Nimitz Library at the United States Naval Academy\n\n{{1861 shipwrecks}}\n{{coord missing|Virginia}}\t<!-- last location reported in the article -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Columbia (1836)}}\n[[Category:Sailing frigates of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:United States Navy South Carolina-related ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Union Navy]]\n[[Category:1836 ships]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Virginia coast]]\n[[Category:Ship fires]]\n[[Category:Scuttled vessels]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in April 1861]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|USS Columbia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{No footnotes|date=October 2011}}\n{|{{Infobox Ship Begin}}\n{{Infobox Ship Image\n|Ship image=Bombardment of Muckie.jpg\n|Ship image size=200px\n|Ship caption=''Columbia'' and ''John Adams'' bombarding Muckie, Sumatra, 1 January 1839\n}}\n{{Infobox Ship Career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1861}}\n|Ship maiden voyage=May 1838\n|Ship name=USS ''Columbia''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Washington Navy Yard]]\n|Ship laid down=1825\n|Ship launched=9 March 1836\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Burned, 21 April 1861\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox Ship Characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{Sclass-|Raritan|frigate}}\n|Ship tonnage= 1726\n|Ship length={{convert|175|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|45|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth={{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=Sail\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=480 officers and men\n|Ship armament=4 \u00d7 {{convert|8|in|mm|abbr=on}} smoothbore guns, 28 \u00d7 32-pounder (15 kg) guns, 22 \u00d7 42-pounder (19 kg) [[carronade]]s\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe first '''USS ''Columbia''''' of the [[United States Navy]] was a three-masted, wooden-hulled sailing [[frigate]] of the [[US Navy]], rated for 50 guns.  She was built at [[Washington Navy Yard]]. Her [[keel]] was laid in 1825, but as was typical of much Navy construction during this period, she was not launched until much later, on 9 March 1836.\n\nOn her first cruise, from May 1838 \u2013 June 1840 with Lieutenant [[George A. Magruder]] in command, ''Columbia'' rounded the [[Cape of Good Hope]] to become [[flagship]] of [[Commodore (United States)|Commodore]] [[George C. Read]] in the [[East India Squadron]]. She returned to the United States by way of [[Cape Horn]], becoming one of the first U.S. naval ships to circumnavigate the globe. She participated in the 1838 [[Second Sumatran Expedition]] in response to a Maylay attack on an American merchant vessel.\n\n''Columbia'' served as flagship of the [[Home Squadron]] from January\u2013May 1842; cruised on [[Brazil Squadron]] from July 1842 \u2013 February 1844 and in the [[Mediterranean Squadron (United States)|Mediterranean Squadron]] from May\u2013December 1844. She returned to the Brazil Squadron as flagship from November 1845 \u2013 October 1847, and was placed [[in ordinary]] at [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] upon her return home. Except for a cruise as flagship of the Home Squadron from January 1853 \u2013 March 1855, she remained at Norfolk until the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]]. ''Columbia'' was scuttled and burned by Union forces to avoid her capture by [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]] upon the surrender of Norfolk Navy Yard on 21 April 1861. Following the close of the war she was raised and sold at Norfolk on 10 October 1867.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Glossary of nautical terms]]\n*[[List of sailing frigates of the United States Navy]]\n\n==References==\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c11/columbia-i.htm}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite book|title=The Flag-ship: Or, A Voyage Around the World in the United States Frigate Columbia..|volume=Volume 2 of The Flag Ship, Or: A Voyage Around the World, in the United States Frigate Columbia; Attended by Her Consort the Sloop of War John Adams, and Bearing the Broad Pennant of Commodore George C. Read, Fitch Waterman Taylor|first=Fitch Waterman|last=Taylor|authorlink=Fitch Waterman Taylor|others=|edition=|year=1840|publisher=D. Appleton and Company|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ENoBAAAAYAAJ| ref=harv }}\n*[https://www.usna.edu/Library/sca/man-findingaids/MS_272.EAD.xml Journal of the U.S.S. ''Columbia'' and U.S.S. ''Mississippi'', 1843-1846 MS 272] held by Special Collection & Archives, Nimitz Library at the United States Naval Academy\n\n{{1861 shipwrecks}}\n{{coord missing|Virginia}}\t<!-- last location reported in the article -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Columbia (1836)}}\n[[Category:Sailing frigates of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:United States Navy South Carolina-related ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Union Navy]]\n[[Category:1836 ships]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Virginia coast]]\n[[Category:Ship fires]]\n[[Category:Scuttled vessels]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in April 1861]]\n", "name_user": "Stonewall61", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Columbia_(1836)"}
